How to Build a Docker Image?

Step 1: Create your app files
mkdir myapp
cd myapp

create a simple HTML file:
echo "<h1>Hello from Docker!</h1>" > index.html

Step 2: Create a Dockerfile
This file tells Docker how to build your image â€” itâ€™s like a recipe.

nano Dockerfile

Paste it.

# Step 1: Use an existing base image
FROM nginx:latest

# Step 2: Copy our HTML file into the nginx web folder
COPY index.html /usr/share/nginx/html/index.html

# Step 3: Expose port 80 (where nginx serves)
EXPOSE 80

ğŸ§© Step 3: Build the image

docker build -t myapp:latest .

ğŸ’¡ Explanation:
docker build â†’ tells Docker to build an image
-t myapp:latest â†’ gives it a name (myapp) and tag (latest)
. â†’ means â€œlook for the Dockerfile in the current folderâ€

ğŸ§© Step 4: Verify your image
docker images

myapp will appear

ğŸ§© Step 5: Run a container from that image
docker run -d -p 8080:80 myapp

Now open your browser â†’
ğŸ‘‰ http://localhost:8080
Youâ€™ll see: â€œHello from Docker!â€

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------
So â€”
âœ… Local Docker â†’ http://localhost:8080
ğŸŒ Remote VM â†’ http://<public-ip>:8080

